ern. Monroe explicates the psychological dehumanization that is a prerequisite for genocide and uses her knowledge of human behavior during the Holocaust to develop a broader theory of moral choice, one applicable to other forms of ethnic, religious, racial, and sectarian prejudice, aggression, and violence. Her book fills a long-standing void in ethics and suggests that identity is more fundamental than reasoning in our treatment of others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aGenocidexMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 0aGenocidexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aTerrorismxMoral and ethical aspectsvCase studies. 0aTerrorismxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aDutch Nazis.  aDutch collaborator.  aDutch plenipotentiary.  aFlorentine van Tonningen.  aGerman soldier.  aHolland.  aHolocaust.  aJewish doctor.  aJews.  aMeinoud Rost van Tonningen.  aNational Socialism.  aNazi Party.  aNazi propagandist.  aNazi supporter.  aNazis.  aWorld War II.  aaggression.  aaltruism.  acavalry officer.  aconservative values.  aconservative views.  adehumanization.  adifference.  adiscrimination.  adisillusionment.  aempirical analysis.  aethical acts.  aethical framework.  aethical political behavior.  aethics.  aethnic cleansing.  aethnic hatred.  agenocide.  ahuman nature.  ahuman psychology.  aidentity.  amoral behavior.  amoral challenges.  amoral choice.  amoral psychology.  apersecution.  apersonal suffering.  apolitical Nazi.  apolitical acts.  apolitical noninvolvement.  apolitical psychology.  aprejudice.  aracism.  aracist views.  areligion.  areligious hatred.  aself-concepts.  aself-image.  aunrepentant.  avalues.  aviolence.  awar bystander.08iTitle is part of 